1. Introduction¶

1.1. As a final project for Pstat 234¶

source: https://www.cvxpy.org/tutorial/advanced/index.html

This project covers three types of location-allocation models which are built with GUROBI-PY. The CVXPY library covered in our lectures provides models only to solve convex problems. But sadly, spatial allocation problems are rarely convex. Street Light Allocation problem is not a convex problem, either. In addition, CVXPY supports gurobi solver with its own grammar, but using gurobi solver via CVXPY is taking one more step to approach gurobi API, so it's more time-comsuming and do not fit for the larger dataset. So CVXPY grammar was replaced to gurobipy grammar in this project. Actually this is first time for me to use gurobipy solver and to learn any python solvers. I really appreciate pstat 234 for the chance.

Also, the python libraries and jupyter notebook functions were used broadly within this project. The numpy, and pandas libraries will be used to manage and calculate the data. And matplotlib, altair libraries will be used for visualizing the data and model results as maps and charts. The selected locations to build street light poles along the road segments will be presented with matplotlib, and the barcharts to check if the model results are sufficiently following the spacing guidelines. This project helped me to get used to python as a tool for managing data and operating models. Also, the jupyter notebook setting helped me to learn Latex codes and markdown language.

1.2. Why Street Lights¶

Have you ever heard of the fact that Artificial Lights consume nearly 20% of total global electricity and account for greenhouse gas emissions of some 1900 Mt(Million tons) of CO2 per year? (OECD/IEA (Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development/Inter-national Energy Agency). World energy outlook 2006. France: OECD/IEA;2006.) Street Lighting is actually a very cost-expensive infrastructure spreaded across human settlements. The spatial decision support system is needed to plan for the network and evaluate the effectiveness.
Besides, street light network is an undeveloped topic within operations research nevertheless it is a mandatory, ubiquotous infrastructure. And the reason is that it could not be developed without GIScience application. So this project is to start the GIS application to the classic operational research models in order to solve street light allocation problem.

To run this notebook again, the jupyter notebook should be launched with anaconda prompt with the environment where gurobipy and python 3 are installed. Also, the academy license from the gurobi, which any member of UCSB could earn simply with email verification, must be installed.

2. Data¶

2.1. Data preprocessed with GIS software¶

For spatial allocation models in this project, the potential facility locations and demand points with the the amount of demand for each point are needed as data. The study region is a census tract in LA city. LA city is firstly selected as a study region because the city government provides real-time updating street light actual location data, which is rare to be seen. The potential locations and demand points were all derived from the Open Street Map road segments(lastly updated at May 23th, 2020) which were divided into the points along the lines with 5 feet distance. The 5 feet distance was determined because the spacing guidelines for the street lights from Bureau of Street Lights (BSL) in LA clarify that for the street lights on major or collector roads are recommended to be spaced at least 60 feet, at most 70 feet. And the street lights on local roads are recommended to be spaced at least 95 feet, at most 170 feet. So to get a meaningful and also feasible results, 5 feet spacing would be desirable as the spacing guideline for major and collector roads gives only 10 feet interval. As a result, this project got 2469 potential street light locations and the same demand points

Some might be wondered about the spacing between street lights because of the two different ways to place street lights along the roads, staggered and one-sided. But actually, those methods don't matter when calculating the space between street lgihts. Even though they are staggered, the space between them is calculated by the distance between the poles along the street centerlines regardless of the side the poles are located. So it's conveient to simplify potential street light locations as points along the road segments.


Now we know how this project derived locations of the potential facility locations and demand points. They are the same in data, but conceptually will be used differently in the models. Still there is one more step, to assign demand values to the demand points. The 2018 landscan daytime and nighttime population data were added up cell-by-cell and added up for each demand points if the cells are within the distance from the demand points. The fixed distance to sum up the population demands was 100 meter for local streets, 200 meter for collector roads, and 300 meter for major roads. This is because the landscan data's cell size is 85 m by 85 m, and as the road hierarchy increases, the road is to cover more demands. The process of generating points along the OSM road segments and calculating demand values was done in ArcGIS Pro, which is a GIS software produced by ESRI. So the result could be read from the csv file. For each demand points, buffer was created and the daytime + nighttime population values from the raster cells simplified into the center points were summed up and assigned as demand value for each demand points.

Within this notebook, the coordinate system will be transformed from meter base into the feet base, sothat when we calculate euclidean distance between two coordinates pair, the result will be within the feet.

2.2. Generating Near Matrix and Distance Matrix¶

The near matrix, N, is going to be used with the two models in this project. The N matrix consists of n rows and n columns. n is the toal number of potential locations. And the row i for each potential location, the column j represents the other potention location. If the N[i,j] value is 1, it means the distance between those potential locations is closer than the minimum spacing guideline. (60 for major and collector roads, 95 for local streets)

Also, the variable D, which is a Distance Matrix, is going to be used with the last model in this project. It contains the distance value beween the two potential locations, i, j in D[i,j].

In [7]:
%%time
n = len(poten)
D = np.zeros([n,n])
N = np.zeros([n,n])

Xs = poten.POINT_X.values
Ys = poten.POINT_Y.values
ST = poten.stype.values

for i in range(len(poten)-1):
    x,y,t =Xs[i], Ys[i], ST[i]
    for j in range(i+1, len(poten)):
        a,b,st = Xs[j], Ys[j], ST[j]
        dist = sqrt((x-a)**2 + (y-b)**2)
        D[i,j], D[j,i] = dist, dist
        const = 60 if [t,st] == [2,2] else 95
        if dist < const:
            N[i,j], N[j,i] = 1,1

3. Models¶

Three models in this project will determine the best set of potential locations to build street lights depending on the various bjective functions and constraints. Mainly, street lights are necessary infrastructure especially for the urban area as LA city. So it should be dispersed as possible even though the dispersed network is not covering the demand at the most. So the 'dispersive strategy' is the core term of all the three models. The dispersive strategies have been used in the location of franchise stores and defensive missile silo placement to maximize the reach-outs, or any unwelcomed facilities need to be dispersed as much as possible to minimize impacts.

The first model solves the street light allocation as an Anti-Covering Location Problem (ACLP) (Murray, A. T., & Church, R. L., 1997). ACLP's objective function is to maximize the demand coverage with selected potential facility locations with a minimum distance constraint that there shouldn't be more than one facilities within the given distance restriction. So ACLP has been applied to various facilities as fire station or police stations, which need to be located as many as possible but should be apart from each other at least some fixed distance.

The second model solves the street light allocation as a Disruptive Anti-Covering Location Problem (DACLP) (Niblett, M. R., & Church, R. L., 2015). DACLP is the worst case solution of an anti-covering problem. And the purpose is to make the solution more dispersed. So the objective function is to minimize the number of selected facility locations not to locate street lights as much as possible. The constraints are that if at any potential location is selected, there shouldn't be any other potential locations selected within the restricted distance. But in case a potential location is not selected, there must be at least one potential location selected within the restricted distance. This kind of model has been used for NIMBY facilities such as landfills and crematoriums.

The last model solves the street light allocation as a P-Median Problem (PMP) (Narula, S. C., Ogbu, U. I., & Samuelsson, H. M., 1977). The objective minimizes the weighted distance of demands assigned to their closest selected potential locations. In other words, the model wants to maximize accessibility to the facilities from the demand users. More accessibility is related to the proper degree of dispersion. The model contains the p constraint, which means that we could choose how many facilities to be located. As this model uses two decision variables, selected locations and assigned demand points to selected locations, it often exhausts the memory. More details will be discussed for each model.

3.1. Anti Covering Location Problem (ACLP)¶

  • referred to (Murray, A. T., & Church, R. L., 1997)
  • with the given distance restriction, maximize the coverage.
  • The most number of street lights to be located with given distance constraint. => get the upper bound


$$ \text{i = index representing potential location sites} $$ $$ a_{i}=\text{benefit associated with the use of location i, demand} $$ $$ d_{ij} = \text{shortest distance from potential facility location i to potential facility location j} $$ $$ S_{min} = \text{restriction distance requirement (no two facilities may be closer than} S_{min} $$ $$ N_{i} = \left \{ j| d_{ij} \leq S_{min} \& i\neq j \right \} $$ $$ |N_{i}| = \text{the number of potential locations within } S_{min} \text{ from potential location i} $$ $$ $$

$$ x_{i} = \left\{\begin{matrix} 1 \,\,\text{if a facility is located at site i} \\ 0 \,\,\,otherwise \end{matrix}\right. $$
$$ $$$$ Maximize\, \, Z = \sum _{i}a_{i}x_{i} $$$$ subject\,to $$$$ $$

$$ |N_{i}|x_{i} + \sum_{j\in N_{i}}^{}x_{j} \leq |N_{i}| \,\ for \, all\ i$$ $$ x_{i} = (0,1) \,\,for\,each\, i $$

Constraint number one, the first row after the text 'subject to', means that when the potential location i is selected sothat xi value becomes 1, the other potential locations within the Smin distance restriction should not be selected. If xi value is 0, potential location i is not selected, the constraint does nothing. So in the code, to run the model faster, the constraint is translated into the different form. In the code, if the potential location i is not selected, total constraint value becomes 0 so the constraint is fullfilled. When the potential location i is selected, we are going to check the other potential locations one by one by multiplying N[i,j] with the decision variable of potential location j. As the constraint value should be zero, no potential location j within the Smin distance from the potential location i (N[i,j] == 1) could be selected.

def distbardata(selected):
    rere = []
    for i in range(len(selected)):
        irow = selected.iloc[i]
        xi = irow['POINT_X']
        yi = irow['POINT_Y']
        si = irow['streetType']
        re = []
        for j in range(len(selected)):
            if i == j:
                continue
            jrow = selected.iloc[j]
            dist = sqrt((xi-jrow['POINT_X'])**2 + (yi-jrow['POINT_Y'])**2)
            sj = jrow['streetType']
            
            if [si,sj] == ['L', 'L']: # Local strets
                col = 'L-L'
            elif [si, sj] in (['M', 'C'], ['C', 'M'], ['M', 'M'], ['C', 'C'] ):   # Major or Collector roads
                col = 'MC-MC'
            else:                # Junctions between local and the other types
                col = 'MC-L'
            re.append([round(dist), col])
        re.sort()
        rere.append(re[0])

    df = pd.DataFrame(rere)
    df.columns = ['dist', 'stype']
    df['percent'] = 1
    hi = df.groupby(['dist', 'stype']).count()
    hi = hi.reset_index()
    total = sum(hi['percent'].values)
    hi['percent'] = hi['percent']/total
    return hi

3.2. Disruptive Aanti Covering Location Problem (DACLP)¶

  • referred to (Niblett, M. R., & Church, R. L., 2015)
  • minimize the number of street lights to be located => get the lower bound
$$ Miminize\, \, Z = \sum _{i}x_{i} $$$$ \text{subject to } $$$$ $$

$$ |N_{i}|x_{i} + \sum_{j\in N_{i}}^{}x_{j} \leq |N_{i}| \,\text{for all i }$$ $$ x_{i} + \sum_{j\in N_{i}}^{}x_{j} \geq 1 \,\text{for all i } $$ $$ x_{i} = (0,1) \,\text{for each i } $$

The second constraint is the core part of this model, DACLP. Any potential locations not selected should have at least one selected locations within the given distance restrictions.

# MIP  model formulation

DACLP = gp.Model('DACLP SL Allocation')

DACLPselect = DACLP.addVars(n, vtype=GRB.BINARY, name='DACLPSelect')

DACLP.addConstrs((gp.quicksum(N[i,j]*DACLPselect[j] for j in range(n))*DACLPselect[i] == 0 for i in range(n)), name='Min')
DACLP.addConstrs((gp.quicksum(N[i,j]*DACLPselect[j] for j in range(n))+DACLPselect[i] >= 1 for i in range(n)), name='Max')

DACLP.setObjective((gp.quicksum(DACLPselect)), GRB.MINIMIZE)

DACLP.optimize()

3.3. P-Median with different P-values¶

  • referred to (Narula, S. C., Ogbu, U. I., & Samuelsson, H. M., 1977)
  • maximize accessibility with given number of facilities! => get the middle steps
  • no distance restriction refelcted into the mdoel.
$$ \text{i = index representing places of demand} $$$$ \text{j = index representing potential facility sites} $$$$ \text{p = number of facilities to be located among sites j} $$$$ a_{i} = \text{demand at place i} $$$$ d_{ij} = \text{shortest distance from demand place i to potential facility site j} $$$$ x_{i} = \left\{\begin{matrix} 1 \,\,\text{if a facility is located at site i} \\ 0 \,\,\,otherwise \end{matrix}\right. $$$$ z_{ij} = \left\{\begin{matrix} 1 \,\,\text{if demand i is assigned to facility j} \\ 0 \,\,\,otherwise \end{matrix}\right. $$
$$ \text{Minimize } Z = \sum_{i}\sum_{j}a_{i}d_{ij}z_{ij} $$

$$ $$ $$ \text{subject to } $$ $$ $$ $$ \sum_{j}z_{ij} = 1 \,\,\text{for all i} $$ $$ z_{ij} \leq x_{j} \,\,\text{for all i,j} $$ $$ \sum x_{j} = p $$ $$ x_{j} = (0,1) \,\,\text{for each j} $$ $$ z_{ij} = (0,1) \,\,\text{for each i,j} $$

Constraint one is to ensure that all demand locations are assigned to a closest facility.
The second constraint is to assign deamnd point to a facility when it is open.
The third constraint is to open p facilities.
The last ocnstraint is the integer restiction, but the z_ij will be relaxed to continuous variable sothat the model could be operable.

def pmediansolver(p):
    print('====================='+str(p)+'=======================')
    start_time = time.time()
    Pmedian = gp.Model('P-median SL Allocation' + str(p))
    Pmedian.Params.NodefileStart = 0.5
    Pmedian.Params.MIPFocus = 2
    
    Pmedianselect = Pmedian.addVars(n, vtype=GRB.BINARY, name='Select')
    Pmedianassign = Pmedian.addVars(n,n, ub=1, vtype=GRB.CONTINUOUS, name='Assign') # linear relaxation

    Pmedian.addConstrs((gp.quicksum(Pmedianassign[(c,f)] for f in range(n)) == 1 for c in range(n)), name='Demand')
    Pmedian.addConstrs((gp.quicksum(N[i,j]*Pmedianselect[j] for j in range(n))*Pmedianselect[i] == 0 for i in range(n)), name='Near')
    Pmedian.addConstrs((Pmedianassign[(c,f)] <= Pmedianselect[f] for c in range(n) for f in range(n)), name='Setup2ship')
    Pmedian.addConstr((gp.quicksum(Pmedianselect) == p), name='Num')

    Pmedian.setObjective((gp.quicksum(demand[i]*D[i,j]*Pmedianassign[i,j] for j in range(n) for i in range(n))), GRB.MINIMIZE)

    Pmedian.optimize()
    
    timespend = time.time() - start_time
    time_exact.append(timespend)
    print("--- %s seconds ---" % (timespend))
    
    idx_selected = []
    for facility in Pmedianselect.keys():
        if (abs(Pmedianselect[facility].x) > 1e-6):
            idx_selected.append(facility)
    pselected = poten.loc[idx_selected]
    dem = pd.Series(demand)
    coverage = sum(dem[idx_selected])
    coverages.append(coverage)
    pmedianY.append(pselected)

charts = []
for i in range(4):
    Pmedianchart = alt.Chart(pmedianY[i], title= str(len(pmedianY[i])) + " locations elected by PMP with demand coverage " + str(sum(pmedianY[i].demand))).mark_point(color='yellow', size=20).encode(
        x=alt.X('POINT_X', scale=alt.Scale(domain=xrange), title="longitude"),  
        y=alt.Y('POINT_Y', scale=alt.Scale(domain=yrange), title="latitude"),
        tooltip=['demand']
    ).interactive()
    
    Pmediandf = distbardata(pmedianY[i])
    Pmediandist =alt.Chart(Pmediandf).mark_bar().encode(
        x= alt.X('dist', scale=alt.Scale(domain=[70,230]), title='distance'),
        y=alt.Y('percent:Q',  axis=alt.Axis(format='.0%'), scale=alt.Scale(domain=[0,0.4]),title='percent'),
        color =alt.Color('stype', scale=alt.Scale(domain=domain, range=range_))
    )

    rule = alt.Chart(pd.DataFrame([60, 70], columns=['guide'])).mark_rule(color="red").encode(
        x = 'guide'
    )
    rule2 = alt.Chart(pd.DataFrame([95, 170], columns=['guide'])).mark_rule(color="blue").encode(
        x = 'guide'
    )
    charts.append(alt.hconcat(
        alt.layer(ct, Pmedianchart), Pmediandist+rule+rule2
    ).resolve_scale(
        color='independent'
    ))
pmediancharts = alt.vconcat(charts[0], charts[1], charts[2], charts[3])
pmediancharts.display()
  • More street Lights( greater p ) means more conformity to spacing guidelines.
  • As p increases, the coverage increment slows down.
  • due to the demand calculation, always major and collector roads are firstly covered.
  • So as p increases, street lights are more evenly distributed.

Out[329]:

  • current Street Light locations could be improved

    From the final chart, we could understand that there is room to improve current street lights efficiency. There are results where the number of street lights could be decreased but the demand coverage could be icreased. By using P-Median Problem model with p- values between 27 and 43, many improvement suggestions could be derived.

  • intersections not considered in model results

    More specifically, the spatial distribution of the located street lights could be discussed further. In the current street light locations map and distance graph, we could discover the fact that there are multiple street lights located redundantly in very close distance. More than 50% of total street lights are not following spacing guidelines from BSL. This is because the number of street lights are incremented as LA city developed for a long time where street light allocation guidelines were not firmly stated. But there are some other redundancy we have to learn from. The computational models results do not consider the intersections where definitely need street light more than any other parts of roads. Some of the redundancy in current street light locations is due to the effor of covering the intersections. With greater p-value assigned, the model shows great contribution to covering intersections but with less p-value, it cannot be enough street lights from the intersections.

  • further applicaiton of GIScience into Operational research

    So in this project, this is a limitation that geographical features in reality were not sufficeiintly reflected into the model. Just the population demands were not sufficient to indicate the models the locations of intersections. However, it is also the proof on how GIScience could contribute to the operational researches.

Conclusion¶

  • The approach of getting upper bound and lower bound from ACLP and DACLP and then consider equity with PMP model is reasonable.
  • Street Light locations could be mainly derived from the float population around road segments.
  • That spacing guidelines are derived from the equity concerns is inferred.
  • More geographical features are to be considered. Especially intersections.
  • P-median model requires much more RAM memory.
